```python
        retries = self.p.reconnect
        if retries >= 0:
            retries += firstconnect

        while retries < 0 or retries:
            if not firstconnect:
                time.sleep(self.p.timeout)

            firstconnect = False

            if self.conn.connect():
                if not fromstart or resub:
                    self.startdatas()
                return True  # connection successful

            if retries > 0:
                retries -= 1
```

What exactly is happening isn't clear. But the code above is the one that takes `self.p.reconnect` into account. If the value is `-1` the loop will run forever because of the condition: `while retries < 0 or ...`.

And the value of `retries` (which is taken from `self.p.reconnect`) is always `< 0` and remains untouched at the end of the loop.

