> I have a feeling that you would need a special case for Return = void because C++ doesn't allow return void.

C++ allows it:
```c++
void foo() {
    return void();
}

void bar() {
    return foo();
}
```
Makes generic code nice and consistent.

> `/root/pycaer/src/pycaer.cpp:42:44:   required from here`

You're trying to bind a `va_list` argument, which isn't possible to bind because it doesn't have any type information.  For C/C++ code using it, you have to already know the type information in some other way, which is pretty much why `va_list` is only useful for things like `printf`-type functions where the format carries the type information.

A simple way to work around it (which also provides a nicer interface from the Python point of view) is to do something like:
```C++
.def("log", [](py::str format, py::args args, py::kwargs kwargs) {
    std::string formatted = format.format(*args, **kwargs);
    libcaer::log::log("%s", formatted.c_str());
})
```
That should work more or less the same, but using Python formatting rather than requiring C-style printf formatting.

